  "riddle": "Here is the revised riddle:\n\n1. Seek the Punjabi village known for its connection to a renowned poet; what geographic coordinates are given for that settlement on its page?\n\n2. There exists a staff college in the high, windswept provincial capital nearby; report how many metres above sea level that city sits.\n\n3. How many other countries have historically sent cadets or officers to the nation’s premier officer-training academy, as recorded on that academy’s article?\n\n4. If you take the numeric total you just found in clue 3, how many positive divisors does that number possess?\n\n5. The article whose subject is an army corps points you to a national statistic — what is the current population of Pakistan according to a reliable country population source?\n\n6. In the narrative of national totals, take the population you found in clue 5 and give the next prime number that comes after it.\n\n7. The regiment once nicknamed the \"Piffers\" still keeps a regimental centre — consult its page and name the town that hosts that centre.\n\n8. (One brief lookup on a neighboring country’s census will help here.) What is the current population of India?\n\n9. Marvel at the Army’s supreme command: state the cantonment, the district, and the province where the main headquarters is located, as listed on its article.\n\n10. Concluding calculation: compute abs(clue 3 - clue 5) % 10 and give the single-digit result (0–9).",
